{"title_page": "Paul Bloom (psychologist)", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian/American psychologist}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Paul Bloom\n| image = Paul Bloom no Fronteiras do Pensamento Florian\u00f3polis 2014 (15062511061).jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|12|24|}}<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.dropbox.com/s/73v6d9bbe82vxjd/paul-bloom-cv-november-2016.pdf?dl=0 | title=Paul-bloom-cv-november-2016.pdf}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| residence = [[New Haven, Connecticut]]\n| citizenship = U.S., Canadian\n| nationality = \n| ethnicity = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| field = [[Psychology]]\n| work_institutions = [[Yale University]]<br />[[University of Arizona]]\n| alma_mater = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]<br />[[McGill University]]\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Susan Carey]]\n| thesis_title = Semantic structure and language development\n| thesis_year = 1990\n| thesis_url = http://hdl.handle.net/1721.1/13686\n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| prizes = \n| footnotes = \n| website = http://campuspress.yale.edu/paulbloom/\n}}\n\n'''Paul Bloom''' (born December 24, 1963) is a [[Canadian American]] psychologist. He is the Brooks and Suzanne Ragen Professor of [[psychology]] and [[cognitive science]] at [[Yale University]]. His research explores how children and adults understand the physical and social world, with special focus on [[Language development|language]], [[morality]], [[religion]], [[fiction]], and [[art]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nBloom was born into a [[Jews|Jewish]] family in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]].<ref name=\"The Atlantic\">{{cite web |work=[[The Atlantic]] |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2005/12/is-god-an-accident/304425/ |title=Is God an Accident? |date=December 2005 |accessdate=17 May 2013}}</ref> As an undergraduate he attended [[McGill University]], where he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in psychology (with honors first class) in 1985. He attended graduate school at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], where he earned a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]] in [[cognitive psychology]] in 1990, under the supervision of [[Susan Carey]].\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 1990 to 1999, he taught psychology and cognitive science at the [[University of Arizona]]. Since 1999, he has been a professor of psychology and cognitive science at Yale University.\n\nSince 2003, Bloom has served as co-editor in chief of the scholarly journal ''[[Behavioral and Brain Sciences]]''.\n\n=== Honors and awards ===\nBloom has held the Harris Visiting Professorship at the Harris Center for Developmental Studies at the [[University of Chicago]] (2002); the Nijmegen Lectureship at the [[Max Planck Institute]] at the [[University of Nijmegen]] (2006); the [[Templeton Foundation|Templeton]] Lectureship at [[Johns Hopkins University]] (2007-8); and the Visiting Distinguished SAGE Fellowship at the [[UCSB]] SAGE Center for the Study of Mind (2010).\n\nIn 2003, the [[Society for Philosophy and Psychology]] awarded Bloom the Stanton Prize for outstanding early-career contributions to interdisciplinary research in [[philosophy]] and psychology, and in 2005-06, he served as the society's president. In 2006, he was made a fellow of the [[American Psychological Society]] in recognition of his \"sustained outstanding contributions to the science of psychology\".\n\nIn 2004, he received the Lex Hixon Prize for teaching excellence in the [[social sciences]] at Yale. In 2007, his Introduction to Psychology class was selected as an outstanding Yale course to be made available worldwide through the [[Open Yale Courses]] initiative.\n\nIn 2017, he received the $1 million 2017 Klaus J. Jacobs Research Prize for his investigations into how children develop a sense of morality.\n\n== Bibliography ==\nBloom is the author of five books and editor or co-editor of three others. His research has appeared in ''[[Nature (magazine)|Nature]]'' and ''[[Science (magazine)|Science]]'', and his popular writing has appeared in ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''The [[American Scientist]]'', ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' and ''[[The Atlantic]]''. His article in ''The Atlantic'', \"Is God an Accident?\" was included in ''[[The Best American Science Writing]]'' 2006. He has had regular appearances on [[National Public Radio]] and [[Bloggingheads.tv]].\n\n=== Books ===\n* Bloom, P. (2016). ''[[Against Empathy: The Case for Rational Compassion]]''. Ecco<ref>Hardcover 2016, {{ISBN|978-0062339331}}</ref>\n* Bloom, P. (2013). ''Just Babies: The Origins of Good and Evil''. The Crown Publishing Group.<ref>Paperback 2014, {{ISBN|978-0307886859}}</ref>\n* Bloom, P. (2010). ''How Pleasure Works: The New Science of Why We Like What We Like''. New York: W. W. Norton & Co.<ref>Paperback reprint 2011, {{ISBN|978-0393340006}}</ref>\n* Bloom, P. (2004). ''Descartes' Baby: How the Science of Child Development Explains What Makes Us Human''. New York: Basic Books.<ref>2005, {{ISBN|978-0465007868}}</ref>\n* Bloom, P. (2000). ''How Children Learn the Meanings of Words''. Cambridge, Massachusetts. MIT Press.\n* [[Ray Jackendoff|Jackendoff, R.]]; Bloom, P.; & [[Karen Wynn|Wynn, K.]] (1999). ''Language, Logic, and Concepts: Essays in Honor of John Macnamara''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: MIT Press.\n* Bloom, P.; Peterson, M.; [[Lynn Nadel|Nadel, L.]]; & Garrett, M. (1996). ''Language and Space''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: MIT Press.\n* Bloom, P. (1994). ''Language Acquisition: Core Readings''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: MIT Press.\n\n=== Selected popular articles ===\n*(March 2014). \"[https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/03/the-war-on-reason/357561/ The War on Reason]\", ''Atlantic Magazine''.\n*(November 2013). \"[http://ideas.time.com/2013/11/13/politicians-really-are-big-babies/ Politicians Really Are Big Babies]\".\n*(January 2012). \"[http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev-psych-120710-100334 Religion, Morality, Evolution]\". ''[[Annual Review of Psychology]]'', vol. 63. [http://www.yale.edu/minddevlab/papers/religion-morality-evolution.pdf Religion, Morality, Evolution].\n*(May 2010). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/09/magazine/09babies-t.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 The Moral Life of Babies]\". ''The New York Times Magazine''.\n*(September 2009). \"The long and short of it\". ''The New York Times''.\n*(August 2009). \"What's Inside a Big Baby Head?\" (Book Review: ''The Philosophical Baby'' by [[Alison Gopnik]]). ''Slate''.\n*(June 2009). \"No Smiting\". (Book Review: ''The Evolution of God'' by [[Robert Wright (journalist)|Robert Wright]]). The New York Times.\n*(November 2008). \"Does religion make you nice?\". ''Slate''.\n*(November 2008). \"First-person Plural\". ''Atlantic Monthly''.\n*(June 2006). \"Seduced by the flickering lights of the brain\". ''Seed Magazine''.\n*(December 2005). \"Is God an accident?\" ''The Atlantic Monthly''.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://campuspress.yale.edu/paulbloom/ Paul Bloom's personal homepage]\n*[http://www.yale.edu/minddevlab/publications.html Links to Bloom's articles and books at Yale]\n* [http://oyc.yale.edu/psychology/introduction-to-psychology/ Introduction to Psychology], video course by Paul Bloom at [[Open Yale Courses]]\n* {{TED speaker}}\n** TED Talk: [http://www.ted.com/talks/paul_bloom_the_origins_of_pleasure Paul Bloom: The origins of pleasure] (TEDGlobal 2011)\n\n{{Evolutionary psychology}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bloom, Paul}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American psychologists]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Developmental psychologists]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona faculty]]\n[[Category:Yale University faculty]]\n[[Category:American science writers]]\n[[Category:Cognitive scientists]]\n[[Category:Canadian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian psychologists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American social scientists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish Canadian writers]]\n[[Category:Evolutionary psychologists]]\n[[Category:Moral psychologists]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Writers from Montreal]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:Developmental psycholinguists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian scientists]]\n[[Category:Writers from New Haven, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Scientists from New Haven, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian/American psychologist}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Paul Bloom\n| image = Paul Bloom no Fronteiras do Pensamento Florian\u00f3polis 2014 (15062511061).jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|12|24|}}<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.dropbox.com/s/73v6d9bbe82vxjd/paul-bloom-cv-november-2016.pdf?dl=0 | title=Paul-bloom-cv-november-2016.pdf}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| residence = [[New Haven, Connecticut]]\n| citizenship = U.S., Canadian\n| nationality = \n| ethnicity = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| field = [[Psychology]]\n| work_institutions = [[Yale University]]<br />[[University of Arizona]]\n| alma_mater = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]<br />[[McGill University]]\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Susan Carey]]\n| thesis_title = Semantic structure and language development\n| thesis_year = 1990\n| thesis_url = http://hdl.handle.net/1721.1/13686\n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| prizes = \n| footnotes = \n| website = http://campuspress.yale.edu/paulbloom/\n}}\n\n'''Paul Bloom''' (born December 24, 1963) is a [[Canadian American]] psychologist. He is the Brooks and Suzanne Ragen Professor of [[psychology]] and [[cognitive science]] at [[Yale University]]. His research explores how children and adults understand the physical and social world, with special focus on [[Language development|language]], [[morality]], [[religion]], [[fiction]], and [[art]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nBloom was born into a [[Jews|Jewish]] family in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]].<ref name=\"The Atlantic\">{{cite web |work=[[The Atlantic]] |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2005/12/is-god-an-accident/304425/ |title=Is God an Accident? |date=December 2005 |accessdate=17 May 2013}}</ref> As an undergraduate he attended [[McGill University]], where he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in psychology (with honors first class) in 1985. He attended graduate school at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], where he earned a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]] in [[cognitive psychology]] in 1990, under the supervision of [[Susan Carey]].\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 1990 to 1999, he taught psychology and cognitive science at the [[University of Arizona]]. Since 1999, he has been a professor of psychology and cognitive science at Yale University.\n\nSince 2003, Bloom has served as co-editor in chief of the scholarly journal ''[[Behavioral and Brain Sciences]]''.\n\n=== Honors and awards ===\nBloom has held the Harris Visiting Professorship at the Harris Center for Developmental Studies at the [[University of Chicago]] (2002); the Nijmegen Lectureship at the [[Max Planck Institute]] at the [[University of Nijmegen]] (2006); the [[Templeton Foundation|Templeton]] Lectureship at [[Johns Hopkins University]] (2007-8); and the Visiting Distinguished SAGE Fellowship at the [[UCSB]] SAGE Center for the Study of Mind (2010).\n\nIn 2003, the [[Society for Philosophy and Psychology]] awarded Bloom the Stanton Prize for outstanding early-career contributions to interdisciplinary research in [[philosophy]] and psychology, and in 2005-06, he served as the society's president. In 2006, he was made a fellow of the [[American Psychological Society]] in recognition of his \"sustained outstanding contributions to the science of psychology\".\n\nIn 2004, he received the Lex Hixon Prize for teaching excellence in the [[social sciences]] at Yale. In 2007, his Introduction to Psychology class was selected as an outstanding Yale course to be made available worldwide through the [[Open Yale Courses]] initiative.\n\nIn 2017, he received the $1 million 2017 Klaus J. Jacobs Research Prize for his investigations into how children develop a sense of morality.\n\n== Bibliography ==\nBloom is the author of five books and editor or co-editor of three others. His research has appeared in ''[[Nature (magazine)|Nature]]'' and ''[[Science (magazine)|Science]]'', and his popular writing has appeared in ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''The [[American Scientist]]'', ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' and ''[[The Atlantic]]''. His article in ''The Atlantic'', \"Is God an Accident?\" was included in ''[[The Best American Science Writing]]'' 2006. He has had regular appearances on [[National Public Radio]] and [[Bloggingheads.tv]].\n\n=== Books ===\n* Bloom, P. (2016). ''[[Against Empathy: The Case for Rational Compassion]]''. Ecco<ref>Hardcover 2016, {{ISBN|978-0062339331}}</ref>\n* Bloom, P. (2013). ''Just Babies: The Origins of Good and Evil''. The Crown Publishing Group.<ref>Paperback 2014, {{ISBN|978-0307886859}}</ref>\n* Bloom, P. (2010). ''How Pleasure Works: The New Science of Why We Like What We Like''. New York: W. W. Norton & Co.<ref>Paperback reprint 2011, {{ISBN|978-0393340006}}</ref>\n* Bloom, P. (2004). ''Descartes' Baby: How the Science of Child Development Explains What Makes Us Human''. New York: Basic Books.<ref>2005, {{ISBN|978-0465007868}}</ref>\n* Bloom, P. (2000). ''How Children Learn the Meanings of Words''. Cambridge, Massachusetts. MIT Press.\n* [[Ray Jackendoff|Jackendoff, R.]]; Bloom, P.; & [[Karen Wynn|Wynn, K.]] (1999). ''Language, Logic, and Concepts: Essays in Honor of John Macnamara''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: MIT Press.\n* Bloom, P.; Peterson, M.; [[Lynn Nadel|Nadel, L.]]; & Garrett, M. (1996). ''Language and Space''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: MIT Press.\n* Bloom, P. (1994). ''Language Acquisition: Core Readings''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: MIT Press.\n\n=== Selected popular articles ===\n*(March 2014). \"[https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/03/the-war-on-reason/357561/ The War on Reason]\", ''Atlantic Magazine''.\n*(November 2013). \"[http://ideas.time.com/2013/11/13/politicians-really-are-big-babies/ Politicians Really Are Big Babies]\".\n*(January 2012). \"[http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev-psych-120710-100334 Religion, Morality, Evolution]\". ''[[Annual Review of Psychology]]'', vol. 63. [http://www.yale.edu/minddevlab/papers/religion-morality-evolution.pdf Religion, Morality, Evolution].\n*(May 2010). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/09/magazine/09babies-t.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 The Moral Life of Babies]\". ''The New York Times Magazine''.\n*(September 2009). \"The long and short of it\". ''The New York Times''.\n*(August 2009). \"What's Inside a Big Baby Head?\" (Book Review: ''The Philosophical Baby'' by [[Alison Gopnik]]). ''Slate''.\n*(June 2009). \"No Smiting\". (Book Review: ''The Evolution of God'' by [[Robert Wright (journalist)|Robert Wright]]). The New York Times.\n*(November 2008). \"Does religion make you nice?\". ''Slate''.\n*(November 2008). \"First-person Plural\". ''Atlantic Monthly''.\n*(June 2006). \"Seduced by the flickering lights of the brain\". ''Seed Magazine''.\n*(December 2005). \"Is God an accident?\" ''The Atlantic Monthly''.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://campuspress.yale.edu/paulbloom/ Paul Bloom's personal homepage]